      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Goblins! Mortgages! It's all about the little, sneaky ways things work, much like how a goblin horde decides which pile of shiny trinkets to raid first. You're asking about the interest versus principal split, and that's a classic financial puzzle, much like trying to herd a particularly mischievous goblin through a narrow cave entrance.\n\nIn the beginning of your 30-year fixed mortgage at 6.5%, the vast majority of your monthly payment is going to the interest, not the principal. Think of it like this: when you first borrow the money, the bank is charging you interest on the *entire* massive pile of debt, which is huge, like a mountain of stolen goblin gold. Because the principal balance is so high at the start, the interest calculation—which is based on that large balance—is also very large.\n\nSo, in Year 5, even though you've been paying diligently, the principal reduction is slow because the interest charge is still dominating the payment. It's like a goblin scout who is so good at hiding that you barely notice they've moved from one patch of moss to another; their progress seems negligible!\n\nAs time marches on, especially moving",
